Data

# Load the data
data(framingham)
length(unique(framingham$RANDID)) ## 4434 patients
## [1] 4434

There are 4434 patients in the Framingham teaching dataset.

to_exclude = framingham |> 
  dplyr::group_by(RANDID) |> 
  dplyr::filter(AGE == min(AGE), ## subset to first visits,
                PREVHYP == 1) |> ## and patients with hypertension at first visit
  dplyr::pull(RANDID) ## create a vector of their IDs
length(to_exclude) # 1430 patients excluded for prevalent hypertension
## [1] 1430

We excluded 1430 patients who had prevalent hypertension at their first visit in the Framingham Study. We then subsetted the data for the remaining patients to include only visits leading up to and including a hypertension diagnosis (or end of followup).

to_analyze = framingham |> 
  dplyr::filter(!(RANDID %in% to_exclude), ## exclude patients with prevalence hypertension (at baseline)
                TIME <= TIMEHYP) ## subset to visits up to and including hypertension diagnosis

The analysis data included each patients first and last visits (either hypertension diagnosis or end of followup), keeping their SYSBP, SEX, AGE, BMI, and TIMEHYP from each.

to_analyze_first = to_analyze |> 
  dplyr::group_by(RANDID) |> 
  dplyr::filter(AGE == min(AGE)) |> 
  dplyr::rename(SYSBP0 = SYSBP, 
                AGE0 = AGE, 
                BMI0 = BMI) |> 
  dplyr::select(RANDID, SEX, AGE0, BMI0, SYSBP0, TIMEHYP) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(TIMEHYP = TIMEHYP / 365, ## convert time from days --> years
                SEX = factor(x = SEX, 
                             levels = c(1, 2), 
                             labels = c("MALE", "FEMALE"))
                ) 

to_analyze_last = to_analyze |> 
  dplyr::group_by(RANDID) |> 
  dplyr::filter(AGE == max(AGE)) |> 
  dplyr::rename(SYSBP1 = SYSBP, 
                AGE1 = AGE, 
                BMI1 = BMI) |> 
  dplyr::select(RANDID, AGE1, BMI1, SYSBP1, HYPERTEN)

to_analyze = to_analyze_first |> 
  dplyr::left_join(to_analyze_last) |> 
  dplyr::mutate(SYSBP_CHANGE = SYSBP0 - SYSBP1)
## Joining with `by = join_by(RANDID)`

We excluded 779 patients who had only one visit before hypertension diagnosis or end of followup.

to_analyze = to_analyze |> 
  dplyr::filter(AGE0 != AGE1) ## subset to patients with at least two visits
nrow(to_analyze) # 2225 patients 
## [1] 2225

Finally, we excluded 7 patients who were missing BMI at their first visit.

to_analyze = to_analyze |> 
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(BMI0)) ## subset to patients with non-missing BMI
nrow(to_analyze) # 2218 patients 
## [1] 2218

These exclusions left a sample of 2218 patients for the analysis of change in systolic blood pressure.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Patients with and without hypertension are described below. From this table, we observe the following:

  • There was a higher proportion of women with hypertension, but a lower proportion of men.
  • On average, patients diagnosed with hypertension tended to be older (by about \(2\) years) than those who were not diagnosed.
  • On average, patients diagnosed with hypertension tended to have higher BMIs (by about \(1\) point) than those who were not diagnosed.
  • On average, patients diagnosed with hypertension tended to have higher systolic blood pressures at both their first and last visits than those who were not diagnosed.

The relationship between systolic blood pressure at first and last visits was positive among patients diagnosed with hypertension or undiagnosed. However, patients diagnosed with hypertension consistently had higher followup systolic blood pressure than patients not diagnosed across all baseline values.

Imputation Model Selection

### Function to make density plot of the distribution of TIMEHYP by diagnosis
density_plot = function(imp_fit, title) {
  imp_fit$imputed_data |> 
    dplyr::mutate(HYPERTEN = factor(x = HYPERTEN, 
                                    levels = c(1, 0), 
                                    labels = c("Diagnosed\n(Uncensored)", "Undiagnosed\n(Censored)"))) |> 
    ggplot(aes(x = imp, fill = HYPERTEN)) + 
    geom_density(alpha = 0.7) + 
    geom_vline(xintercept = 25, linetype = 2) + 
    ggthemes::scale_fill_colorblind(name = "Patient\nStatus:") +
    theme_minimal() + 
    theme(legend.position = "right") + 
    xlab("Time to Hypertension Diagnosis\n(Observed or Imputed)") + 
    ylab("Density") + 
    ggtitle(title) + 
    xlim(c(0, 160))
}

Comparing Imputed Values

Models

Naive Analysis (Time to Hypertension or End of Followup)

Among all 2218 patients, whether or not they were diagnosed with hypertension, the adjusted relationship between their systolic blood pressures at the first and last visits is as follows. Note that time to hypertension or end of followup is being used naively in place of time to hypertension.

naive_fit = lm(SYSBP1 ~ SYSBP0 + TIMEHYP + SEX + AGE0 + BMI0, 
               data = to_analyze)
knitr::kable(coefficients(summary(naive_fit)), digits = 3)
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 112.101 4.007 27.973 0.000
SYSBP0 0.220 0.026 8.600 0.000
TIMEHYP -1.042 0.042 -24.992 0.000
SEXFEMALE -0.048 0.523 -0.091 0.927
AGE0 0.154 0.033 4.702 0.000
BMI0 -0.006 0.078 -0.080 0.936 
knitr::kable(confint(naive_fit), digits = 3)
2.5 % 97.5 %
(Intercept) 104.243 119.960
SYSBP0 0.170 0.270
TIMEHYP -1.124 -0.960
SEXFEMALE -1.072 0.977
AGE0 0.090 0.219
BMI0 -0.160 0.147 
forest_dat = coefficients(summary(naive_fit)) |> 
  data.frame() |> 
  dplyr::mutate(Coefficient = rownames(coefficients(summary(naive_fit))),
                Method = "Naive Analysis") |> 
  dplyr::inner_join(
    confint(naive_fit) |> 
      data.frame() |> 
      dplyr::mutate(Coefficient = rownames(confint(naive_fit))) |> 
      magrittr::set_colnames(c("LB", "UB", "Coefficient"))
  )
## Joining with `by = join_by(Coefficient)`
  • Higher systolic blood pressures at first visit were associated with higher systolic blood pressures at last visit. On average, for every 1 mmHg higher a patients systolic blood pressure was at first visit, their systolic blood pressure was expected to be 0.22 mmHg higher at last visit.
  • Patients who were farther from a hypertension diagnosis at first visit (i.e., larger TIMEHYP) were expected to have lower systolic blood pressures at last visit, on average. Specifically, for every \(1\) year farther away they were from their hypertension diagnosis at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure at that time was expected to be 1.042 mmHg lower at their last visit.
  • Patients who were older at their first visit had higher systolic blood pressures at their last visit, on average. For every year older a patient was at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure was expected to be -0.048 mmHg higher at last visit.
  • Patients with higher BMIs at their first visit hadlower systolic blood pressures at their last visit, on average. For every \(1\) point higher a patients BMI was at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure was expected to be 0.154 mmHg lower at last visit.

Specifically, for every \(1\) year farther away they were from their hypertension diagnosis at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure at that time was expected to be 0.994 mmHg lower at their last visit.
  • Patients who were older at their first visit had higher systolic blood pressures at their last visit, on average. For every year older a patient was at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure was expected to be -0.515 mmHg higher at last visit.
  • Patients with higher BMIs at their first visit hadlower systolic blood pressures at their last visit, on average. For every \(1\) point higher a patients BMI was at their first visit, their systolic blood pressure was expected to be 0.188 mmHg lower at last visit.

Multiple Imputation Analysis

set.seed(333)
## Fit analysis model to each imputed dataset
lognorm_imp = cmi_fp_analytical(imputation_model = Surv(time = TIMEHYP, event = HYPERTEN) ~ SEX + AGE0 + BMI0 + SYSBP0, 
                                dist = "lognormal", 
                                data = to_analyze, 
                                boots = 20)
mult_fit = do.call(what = rbind,
                   args = lapply(X = lognorm_imp,
                                 FUN = function(l) {
                                   summary(lm(formula = SYSBP1 ~ SYSBP0 + imp + SEX + AGE0 + BMI0, data = l$imputed_data))$coefficients
                                 }
                   )
)

## Pool estimates
### Take sums of estimates and variances
sum_est_var = rowsum(x = mult_fit[, 1:2],
                     group = rownames(mult_fit))
### Divide by the number of imputations to get means
mean_est_var = sum_est_var / 20

## Save parameter estimates
mean_est_var
##                 Estimate Std. Error
## (Intercept) 125.70896749 4.09608795
## AGE0          0.17803173 0.03161986
## BMI0         -0.13489513 0.07676702
## imp          -0.51261545 0.01825457
## SEXFEMALE    -0.74492323 0.50796363
## SYSBP0        0.09059939 0.02647921
rownames(mean_est_var)[4] = "TIMEHYP"
forest_dat = mean_est_var |>
  data.frame() |> 
  dplyr::mutate(Coefficient = rownames(mean_est_var),
                Method = "Multiple Imputation Analysis", 
                LB = Estimate - 1.96 * Std..Error, 
                UB = Estimate + 1.96 * Std..Error) |>
  dplyr::bind_rows(forest_dat)

Comparing Methods

Comparing Imputation Models

set.seed(333)
forest_dat = data.frame()
for (d in c("lognormal", "weibull", "exponential", "loglogistic", "pwe")) {
  ## Fit analysis model to each imputed dataset
  imp = cmi_fp_analytical(imputation_model = Surv(time = TIMEHYP, event = HYPERTEN) ~ FEMALE + AGE0 + BMI0 + SYSBP0, 
                          dist = d, 
                          data = to_analyze, 
                          boots = 20,
                          nintervals = 10)
  mult_fit = do.call(what = rbind,
                     args = lapply(X = imp,
                                   FUN = function(l) {
                                     summary(lm(formula = SYSBP1 ~ SYSBP0 + imp + SEX + AGE0 + BMI0, data = l$imputed_data))$coefficients
                                   }
                     )
  )
  
  ## Pool estimates
  ### Take sums of estimates and variances
  sum_est_var = rowsum(x = mult_fit[, 1:2],
                       group = rownames(mult_fit))
  ### Divide by the number of imputations to get means
  mean_est_var = sum_est_var / 20
  
  ## Save parameter estimates
  mean_est_var
  rownames(mean_est_var)[4] = "TIMEHYP"
  forest_dat = mean_est_var |>
    data.frame() |> 
    dplyr::mutate(Coefficient = rownames(mean_est_var),
                  Method = toupper(d), 
                  LB = Estimate - 1.96 * Std..Error, 
                  UB = Estimate + 1.96 * Std..Error) |>
    dplyr::bind_rows(forest_dat)  
}
